227":"1227","1225":"1225","1223":"1223","1157":"1157","Abt 1177":"about 1177","1177":"1177","1161":"1161","Poiteau, Aquitaine, France":"Poujeau, Gironde, Aquitaine, France","Plessis, Morbihan, Bretagne, France":"Le Plessix, Morbihan, Brittany, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Des","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["North German (<b>Düs</b>):","topographic name from Westphalian dialect <i>dūs</i> ‘pile, decay’.","variant of   Duis  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Duis","meanings":["North German and Dutch: from a personal name derived from the name <i>Theodorus</i> (see   Theodore  ) or from a personal name based on the ancient Germanic element <i>theud</i> ‘people, race’."]}]},{"name":"Breux","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Lucien, Ulysse, Andre, Andree, Antoine, Gaston, Gracien, Pierre, Raoul.","Altered form of French   Brault  , itself a variant of   Braud  . This surname is also common among African Americans. Compare   Breau  ,   Breaud  ,   Bro  , and   Brow  .","History: The majority of the Breaux families of LA trace their origins to one Vincent Brault from La Chaussé in Vienne, who arrived in Acadia sometime before 1661 (see also   Brault  ). After the expulsion of the Acadians (1755–64), several of his descendants found their way to LA."],"variants":[{"name":"Brault","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Adelard, Alain, Andre, Gilles, Rosaire, Solange, Cecile, Emile, Francoise, Germaine, Girard.","French: variant of   Braud  . Its most common American French form is   Breaux  ; it was Americanized (Anglicized) as   Brow  ,   Broe  , and   Bro  . Compare   Breault  .","Altered form of American French   Breaux   back to its original form."]},{"name":"Breau","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Ulysse, Alcide, Antoine, Aurore, Girard, Leonide, Mederic, Ovila, Raoul, Yves, Yvon.","American French: variant of   Breaux  , and an altered form of its French cognates   Braud   and   Brault  .","French (<b>Bréau</b>): variant of <b>Breuil</b> (see   Dubreuil  )."]},{"name":"Breaud","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Urbain, Nemour.","American French: variant of   Breaux  .","In some cases possibly also French (<b>Bréaud</b>): variant of   Beraud  , a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Aelis","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Alice","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."]},{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Aelis Des Breux was born in 1161, in Poujeau, Gironde, Aquitaine, France. She had at least 1 son with William du Plessis I. She died in 1223, in Le Plessix, Morbihan, Brittany, France, at the age of 62."},"et":{"1161–1223":"1161–1223","1157–1225":"1157–1225","1177–1227":"1177–1227","1227":"1227","1225":"1225","1223":"1223","1157":"1157","Abt 1177":"umbes 1177","1177":"1177","1161":"1161","Poiteau, Aquitaine, France":"Poujeau, Gironde, Aquitaine, Prantsusmaa","Plessis, Morbihan, Bretagne, France":"Le Plessix, Morbihan, Bretagne, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1161–1223":"1161–1223","1157–1225":"1157–1225","1177–1227":"1177–1227","1227":"1227","1225":"1225","1223":"1223","1157":"1157","Abt 